{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"76045a95-4db4-42c6-bd24-4e83f5974174","content":"You have a few options:\n\n1. **Install as a global tool (requires SDK):**\n   ```bash\n   dotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n   ```\n   But since you don't have the SDK, use option 2 or 3 instead.\n\n2. **Download the standalone (no SDK needed):**\n   ```bash\n   curl -sSL https://aka.ms/dotnet-trace/linux-x64 -o dotnet-trace\n   chmod +x dotnet-trace\n   ```\n\n3. **Copy from a sidecar or `docker cp`:**\n   Download it locally, then:\n   ```bash\n   docker cp ./dotnet-trace <container_id>:/tmp/dotnet-trace\n   ```\n\nOnce inside the container, collect a CPU trace:\n\n```bash\n# Find your app's PID\n./dotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling -o /tmp/trace.nettrace\n```\n\nThen copy it out with `docker cp` and open it in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or **Speedscope** (`--format speedscope`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1d2d3cc2-c1a8-4bda-95da-369f28134828","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Linux container without the .NET SDK. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code task. I can answer this directly.","outputTokens":329},"id":"6e55f708-75d0-4ac0-b7de-b0add0e784ab","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:53:55.592Z","parentId":"601ea5ae-d66c-46e0-8bc9-89d1925f1ab9"}
